Removing unwarranted tags. The lede section isn't meant to provide sources; instead, it is meant to summarise the contents of the article, which it does quite well. The history of the debate is described in the respective section, which thoroughly sourced. The differences between specific groups are also described in the section "group differences". Weasel words are also acceptable in the lede if they are clarified later on in the article (which they are).

/* Spearman's hypothesis */ Corrected grammar and made the sentence more coherent. Also, for reference, g-loading is the extent to which general cognitive ability is measured - not general cognitive ability itself.

Thanks for reverting some of my accidental removals, including Switzerland. However, the UK is a controversial case, with many describing it as a nation state (see the entry on the United Kingdom under the "Modern multinational or multiethnic states" section).

/* Environmental influences on group differences in IQ */ Okay, seems like two editors around here don't want a good summary of views on the topic. At least removed WP:UNDUE as per Rindermann's recent comprehensive survey. It also doesn't make sense to mention "one group" without mentioning 'the other group'. That's like "on the one hand" without saying "on the other hand".
/* Spearman's hypothesis */ Corrected punctuation and disambiguated the statement.

/* Environmental influences on group differences in IQ */ I believe this is a misunderstanding; my addition of the group of scholars which view genetic factors as plausible was not inadvertent and was furthermore justified in the respective edsum. You revert also introduced grammatical and factual errors which had previously been fixed. If you believe that your version is better than the status quo, please first gain consensus for it on the talk page.

"Still" does not imply that the causes will soon or eventually be found; instead, it implies that the question first posed in the 1920s remains (i.e. is still) unanswered. I thought about it and had to come back to this: to claim that the scientific consensus is that there are NO genetic differences in intelligence between populations is just misleading. Even if populations genetically differ only by a fraction of an IQ point, that is a still a difference. And the scientific consensus about intelligence is that it is influenced by genes, which implies that populations will have genetic intellectual differences, even if they are very small.

The ''Oxford English Dictionary''' and even the compact edition often quotes early usages of the word being defined. The fact that the phrase is in quotes tells readers that it was copied exactly from the source, archaic spelling and all. "[sic]" is an additional warning to readers that the spelling is the way it was in the source, even though it doesn't follow modern spelling rules.
